{
  "s1": {
    "grammar": [
      "The poem opens with an accusative-infinitive construction: 'animus fert (me) dicere formas mutatas in nova corpora'.",
      "'In nova...corpora' is an example of hyperbaton - the preposition and adjective are separated from the noun they modify."
    ],
    "vocabulary": [
      "'fert animus' is an idiom meaning 'my mind inclines/leads me to', not literal 'carries'.",
      "'mutatas' (< muto) is a perfect passive participle modifying 'formas'."
    ],
    "context": [
      "This is the proem (invocation) of the poem. Ovid announces his theme: transformation.",
      "Unlike Virgil's 'arma virumque cano', Ovid's opening is notably casual and personal."
    ]
  },
  "s2": {
    "grammar": [
      "'di' (nominative plural of 'deus') is the subject. 'coeptis' is a dative/ablative plural of the perfect participle 'coeptum'.",
      "'nam vos mutastis et illas' - 'et' here means 'also', not just 'and'."
    ],
    "vocabulary": [
      "'adspirate' (< adspiro) means 'breathe upon favorably', 'inspire'.",
      "'primaque ab origine mundi' - 'origo' here means 'beginning, origin'."
    ],
    "context": [
      "The invocation to the gods rather than the Muses is unusual. Ovid implicates the gods themselves in the transformations.",
      "'ad mea...tempora' - Ovid promises a continuous narrative from creation to his own time (the reign of Augustus)."
    ]
  },
